<article>
    <h1>Shift&#xAD;ing be&#xAD;tween sleep and wak&#xAD;ing</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201209/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-09"><time>2020-12-09</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline">DANCE HYPNAGOGIA&#xD;&#xA;Sigma Con&#xAD;tem&#xAD;po&#xAD;rary Dance Face&#xAD;book Live, last Sun&#xAD;day</span>
    </section>

    <p>It is bright day­light in a spa­cious bun­ga­low, but ev­ery­where you turn, you are sur­rounded by omi­nous lurch­ing fig­ures.</p>
    <p>It feels un­nerv­ingly like a zom­bie shooter game, mi­nus the gore.</p>
    <p>Hypnagogia (mean­ing the lim­i­nal state be­tween sleep and wak­ing) is chore­og­ra­pher-direc­tor Hong Guofeng’s lat­est foray into dance as a dig­i­tal ad­ven­ture.</p>
    <p>He breaks new ground as he re­sponds to pan­demic lim­i­ta­tions with a well-con­sid­ered use of tech­nol­ogy and site.</p>
    <p>A 300-de­gree view (mi­nus the videog­ra­pher) tracks 10 dancers through a se­ries of rooms. View­ers can scroll around to dis­cover the ac­tion.</p>
    <p>Lo-fi scenog­ra­phy and Red­wan Hamzah’s shift­ing au­dio land­scapes work ef­fec­tively to make the house a char­ac­ter in it­self.</p>
    <p>The viewer jour­neys through a pro­gres­sion of scenes, in­clud­ing a psy­che­delic disco-light rave, a duet in a hall­way full of dry leaves and a room­ful of as­sorted mir­rors that scat­ter the vis­ual of the dancers’ bod­ies across the space.</p>
    <p>In a strangely macabre room, colour­ful um­brel­las sprout from the walls and a mo­tion­less fig­ure sprawls on the floor in a skele­ton suit while other fig­ures dance out­side the win­dows.</p>
    <p>Dif­fer­ent dates on a tra­di­tional tear-a-day cal­en­dar sug­gest that time is shift­ing be­tween rooms, even as the piece is uni­fied by mo­tifs of um­brel­las, mir­rors and the spi­ralling yet an­gu­lar move­ments un­der­ly­ing scat­tered so­los.</p>
    <p>The con­clu­sion is con­vivial, if a tad ob­vi­ous. The dancers fi­nally con­gre­gate in the main hall to a folksy acous­tic song, then ad­vance down a cor­ri­dor to­gether.</p>
    <p>They pop in and out of a kitchen counter win­dow in a se­ries of strik­ing tableaux. Then slowly, they fade like mem­o­ries from an empty house.</p>
    <p>The ad­ven­ture lasts only 20 min­utes, but in­vites enough cu­rios­ity for au­di­ences to keep re-en­ter­ing over the 24 hours that the live stream is avail­able for.</p>
    <p>The sub­se­quent per­for­mance on Sun­day will be a new live record­ing.</p>

